  <div class="container">
    <h2>The OS - Operating Systems</h2>

    <div class="os-cards">
      <div class="card">
        <h3><a href="windows.html">Windows</a></h3>
        <p>Windows is a proprietary OS widely used for personal computers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3><a href="linux.html">Linux</a></h3>
        <p>Linux is an open-source OS known for its flexibility and security.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3><a href="macos.html">MacOS</a></h3>
        <p>MacOS is a proprietary OS designed for Apple's devices.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Understanding Operating Systems</h2>
      <div class="os-cards">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>What is an OS?</h3>
          <p>An Operating System manages computer hardware and software resources, bridging the gap between users and machines.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Proprietary OS</h3>
          <p>Owned by a single company, proprietary OSs keep their source code private. Examples include Windows and MacOS.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Open-Source OS</h3>
          <p>Freely available and modifiable, open-source OSs encourage community collaboration. Linux is a prime example.</p>

    </section>
  </div>

